Best of luck, and if you have any questions related to breaking into the #entrylevel #datascience job market, donâ€™t hesitate to contact me here or via email.

Finally, if you want to stand out, have a website/portfolio/blog that showcase(s) your interest and passion in data science. These will not only help you in applying for jobs, but people may also reach out to you with freelance projects, interviews, and speaking engagements.

Side Note: If youâ€™re interested in medicine, Iâ€™d recommend doing research w/ a department that does epidemiological/biostatistical studies. Youâ€™ll learn not only stats/programming, but also experimental design and causal inference that can extend far beyond medical applications.

Also, presenting the results of your research to your mentors and others at conferences will greatly improve your public speaking skills and networking circles. I had the honor of presenting my research at #WSDS2017, #JMM2018, and #SIAMUQ18 thanks to some #UROP research grants.

Research positions that use stats/computer science skills arenâ€™t necessarily all concentrated in the stats/computer science departments. You can learn and perform useful stats/computer science work in any university department, from philosophy to political science to biology.

Continuing yesterday's thread: if you feel comfortable with your stats/programming/computer science skills, then I would highly recommend you apply for industry internships or research positions at your university.

A great way to learn #rstats is to read @hadleywickham's freely-available book, R for Data Science (https://t.co/IdFhuCwLYx). An even better way is to learn with the #rstats community by joining awesome #rlady @kierisi's online #r4ds learning community (https://t.co/rnkOuU7sqN)
I'd also recommend @jhubiostats Chromebook Data Science program (which is also free!): https://t.co/NlPUxBcCay
Some courses Iâ€™ve taken that Iâ€™d recommend are MITâ€™s and Harvard's Intro to Comp Sci courses and Stanfordâ€™s Machine Learning course by @AndrewYNg (https://t.co/4jMWAsJLdu).

If you donâ€™t have much of a stats/programming/computer science background or would like to improve your skills in any of these areas, Iâ€™d advise you to either fit some stats/computer science courses into your schedule or take free, online courses from @coursera and @edXOnline.

ğŸ‘†Even if you are not interested in extending ggplot2 - the tutorial is fun to read, because it also gives you a bit of a ggplot2 history lesson. 

Additionally, I also learn from already published ggplot2 extensions: https://t.co/3uLXNKPXCk and see how other people managed.

My main learning source is this tutorial: 

https://t.co/xZ4uOXylwR

It starts easy and then increases in difficulty, so ideal for gentle learning. Checkout the examples at the bottom of each section.

(for me, this meant to actually read some documentation)

When creating a new stat, you can inherit a geom. But to create a new geom, you will need to use {grid} - which is fun to learn!

Making your own geom or stat requires a bit of an effort because the underlying principle of ggplot2 is not easy to grasp (while ggplot2 itself is super intuitive). Extending ggplot2 requires you to understand how ggproto() works.

{ggplot2} offers tons of options to accomplish what you want to visualise. 

But sometimes you want to use a custom stat or geom, that cannot be assembled form what exists.

The good thing about leaflet is that you have a base map that shows geospatial features & allows panning around and zooming in and out. 
This makes it easier to get an idea of the surrounding area, and whether you've achieved whatever you were trying to do.

The syntax of the leaflet package will feel familiar to those of you who use pipes. It also resembles ggplot in that you add successive layers:

leaflet() %>% addTiles(., ) %>% 
addPolygons(., data = polygon) %>% 
addMarkers(., data = points) %>% 
addPolylines(., data = line) https://t.co/9jJ58ahDe5

The 3rd package I want to mention is leaflet, which is used for visualisation.
This is a key part of checking whether something has worked. 
Here we plotted points we identified as cul-de-sacs using leaflet. You can see we've missed cul-de-sacs with roundabouts on them (in red) https://t.co/Qf9gbCnHnH

This is basic stuff, but it often forms the foundation of some pretty cool geospatial work. 
We've calculated many metrics for home insurance using these. e.g. Distance to main road, number of access points that a dwelling has, how far dwellings are from fire stations, etc.

Once you've got your spatial data & it's in right projection, what kind of stuff might you want to do with it?

The rgeos package allows you to:
- Add a buffer to something
- Calculate distances between objects
- Test whether 2 things intersect
- Find the centre of something
I have to duck out for a meeting, but when I'm back, I'd like to talk about a couple of other packages I use for geospatial work

The unit of measurement for projected coordinate systems is typically meters, while latitude-longitude projections use degrees. 
A lot of problems in geospatial work comes from objects having different / the wrong projections. I always check this first!

Spatial projections differ in how things are measured, and how we translate a 3D globe into 2D. 

Geographic projections measure coordinates from the center of the earth, while planimetric ones project the earths coordinates onto a 2D surface.

The sp package allows you to create spatial objects and transform their projections. 
Projections are very important in spatial work! 
They define how something is located and shown within space. (I find this a difficult concept to explain - anyone got a better definition?)

You can also create spatial objects from text data. For example, you can take a csv of latitude and longitude of dwellings and create SpatialPoints using the package sp. 
This package also allows you to work with SpatialPolygons and SpatialLines. https://t.co/m2FDJXUPGW

Raster data is made up of pixels or cells, each of which has an associated value. 

I use rasters of elevation like this LiDAR of Auckland, which captures the elevation at an accuracy of 1 m squared. https://t.co/zhgMZbZSh8

Spatial data comes in different forms from your typical text data. Shapefiles are a form of vector data that usually show you the boundaries of a polygon. For example, I use shapefiles of the regional councils and postcodes that make up NZ. https://t.co/Lzb2Ygwmrv

I do quite a lot of geospatial work to predict natural perils like flood and storm in New Zealand. This involves things like extracting the elevation of dwellings, calculating the distance between dwellings and rivers and the coast, etc.

Today I'd like to talk about some of the geospatial work I do in R in a bit more detail, and hopefully also get your input on areas where I don't know as much. 
(And yes I am convinced this will be my only useful skill in the case of an apocalypse ğŸ˜†) https://t.co/QEWSj1kr0W

The feature problem is harder to solve (ideas welcome!) But I guess all this is to say that
1. Algorithms can be biased, and often this reflects human biases against minority groups
2. Training data & feature selection are super important!

For the revamp in R, Iâ€™m using data from the Auckland marathon as my training set. Itâ€™s classified by gender and has a much wider range of names in it (although there are still biases - for example, more men participate in the marathon than women, so I also included the 5k data)

I used the 100 most common baby names of babies born in NZ going back to 1950. It doesnâ€™t include people who immigrated here & a name has to be pretty common to make the list. I also added in the most common MÄori names, but these lists are shorter & don't go back as far https://t.co/wq1mmaAoKO

I think the problem is twofold: My training data was biased towards English names & the features reflect an English way of specifying gender (Male names in English tend to end in a consonant, while female names tend to end in vowels - but this doesn't hold across other languages)

The algorithm does a pretty OK job, but not great. It does particularly badly on predicting the gender of names from certain ethnicities, i.e not English names. I took a closer look at MÄori (indigenous NZ) names and found that it didnâ€™t really understand male MÄori names at all. https://t.co/Bb658WKDha

So I used a gender classification algorithm I wrote a while back. Itâ€™s currently in python, but I am working on rewriting and improving it in R. 
Basically it takes the last letter and last 2 letters of the first name as features & predicts gender based on that.

This gave me the names and party affiliations of the Members of Parliament, but not their gender. Often we can tell from their first name, but manually classifying almost 1000 names by gender doesnâ€™t sound like a data science way of doing things.

Fellow data table enthusiasts - I know that there are at least a couple of you out there! Have I missed anything (without diving into the DT syntax)?
Melt and dcast are faster ways of reshaping data (the equivalent of gather & spread). To take advantage of data tables fast joins, you can use setkey and then merge on that key.

This sounds trivial, but data table prints out the top & bottom 5 rows when you run the name of the data table. Not only does this save you from using head or tail, it also stops R from crashing when it tries to print out a couple of million rows. https://t.co/1dJVro9GSI
The functions fwrite and fread are super fast ways of reading in / writing to csv. Here is a comparison of reading in just over 2 million rows. https://t.co/4a45Ydi2Id

If you're a dplyr fan, why is that? I'm going to duck out and do some work for a bit, but I'd love to know what you like about it ğŸ˜€ And do you ever run into issues with speed?

@the_engi_nerd I use data table, and because I'm used to it & like its other features, I use it even on small datasets. 
In terms of text data (i.e. not shapefiles etc), I would get up to several million rows. E.g. NSW in Australia has 7.5 million people - we might deal with the state in one go

If your datasets are pretty big, this will literally save you hours. Geospatial data is often really big - even little old New Zealand has over 2 million dwellings. Reading that in & manipulating it is so much faster using data table.

Using dataframes (and dplyr) is basically the equivalent of moving the entire house to the building site in order to add on a single room. 
Because of that, itâ€™s slow. Data table, on the other hand, adds the room on where the house already exists.

Data table, on the other hand, uses a pass-by-reference approach, which means if a function internally changes something, the object outside is also changed, since you didn't pass it a copy, but a pointer to the real thing.

@el_abstemio Data table, but I also don't like to be too prescriptive - if you know dplyr really well and don't work with very big datasets, it probably works for you. I'd be keen to hear why people prefer dplyr.

Why is that? (Iâ€™m not a computer scientist and Iâ€™m sure some of you can explain this better). Dataframes are not changed when you pass them into a function - a copy is made and the copy is changed before being given back to you.
@JimGrange I've heard this being mentioned before, and if you don't tend to work with very big datasets and you're used to dplyr, it might be reason to stick with it

Here we can see how data table compares to dplyr, pandas in python, and a bunch of other options when doing some basic operations on  a big dataset. Itâ€™s a lot faster! This is true for reading data in, adding columns, merging, reshaping, etc. https://t.co/HSXSod9fAR

Dplyr seems hugely popular, especially on Twitter. But - controversial opinion here - I donâ€™t use it. 
The main reason being that it is sloowww and that starts to make a real difference when youâ€™re working with big datasets (which is often the case with geospatial data).

We can extract the end point of each line & add a smaller buffer to those end points (done using the gBuffer function from rgeos). Now we can test whether each buffered end point intersects with any other end points. If it does - the road continues! If not, itâ€™s a cul-de-sac!

We have every road in Australia as a Spatial Line (a type of spatial data that you can create & deal with using the sp package). Every time lines intersect, a new line starts. So at an intersection, you have 4 line segments coming together in the middle

I really like doing this kind of stuff in R, because you have to think about things in a very different way than with most other types of analyses. 
Coming back to my example, how would you even begin to find every dwelling thatâ€™s in a culdesac?

For example, I found every house in Australia thatâ€™s in a culdesac (Less people going through might reduce theft, but access for fire engines is harder and increases fire risk). Hereâ€™s a quick screenshot of visual checks I did using the package leaflet to make sure it was working https://t.co/nVPn2rkHvw

So - #rspatial work in insurance! Other than natural perils (which I will talk about at some point) itâ€™s also used to identify the features of individual dwellings that might impact their risk of things like burglary or malicious damage.

Tweet.text: Since my academic background is in Economics, I can speak a little to the changing landscape in the discipline. As we're starting to adopt and experiment with a wider variety of methods in Econ (ML, NLP etc.), Stata will start to feel more and more limiting.

Without getting into language wars, I'll say this - there are plenty of good reasons to transition from Stata to R. 

â­ï¸R is open-source and free!
â­ï¸Far nicer visualizations
â­ï¸Easier to work with multiple datasets
â­ï¸More resources and documentation
â­ï¸More 'general-purpose'

Some of the things I want to talk about and share this week include the things I wish I'd known when I just started using R, making the transition from Stata to R painless and building a repository of #rstats resources in languages other than English.

My favourite thing about R is how accessible it is to people without traditional CS training and how rapidly it is evolving from a statistical computing platform to something that's more multi-purpose and 'full-stack'.

I use a lot of R at my job for cleaning, wrangling and visualizing data. I find myself switching back and forth between Python and R, simply depending on what tasks I know to accomplish in which language.

Ok your ğŸ“¦ is written now what? 

1. Devtools::install to create OR
2. Build tab in Rstudio click install & restart
3. Share on GitHub with install_github("username/packagename")
4. Devtools:build to create a zipped tar.gz file of your package

@RLadiesNYC #rstats #rtips https://t.co/g4SDYfwaOt

To expose your functions to users and generate them in your namespace file, write:
# ' @export in your .r file in front of your function 

Don't edit your namespace by hand for this! Run devtools:document() instead.

Include dependencies, packages, and versions under Imports in your namespace file.
@RLadiesNYC #rstats #rtips
Usethis::use_packages can help you write vignettes and documentation for your new ğŸ“¦

Recommendation: when using functions from other packages in your new package write it as package::function in your .r file.

But if you want to use %>% import via importFrom(dplyr, '%>%') in your namespace file for efficiency sake

Each package has: 
1. R/directory - has your .r files
2. Description file - describes ğŸ“¦
3. Namespace file - has functions that you want your users to see
4. .rproj - rstudio project

Fast forward to 2017. I had just finished a semester abroad at UNC Chapel Hill studying public health and had decided this is probably what I want to do. I was encouraged by a friend to take up coding again. Started with Python but gravitated to #rstats and here I am, I guess!

Now, I KNOW THIS IS NOT ACTUALLY THE CASE, and that is important! Today, in the #rstats world, that is not how I feel. But as an 18 yo trying to decide on my future, I couldn't see myself pursuing that career.

However, there was one thing that made me think twice and in the end made me choose another path (which I don't regret, but you know, what if): visiting schools I felt like coding was 100% a boy's club. All men, and I didn't really feel welcome.

When I started applying to university I was considering going into data engineering or data science or maybe software development, because I felt like I had found something that was fun, rewarding and hey I felt like I was pretty good at it!

So, in high school (or, the Swedish equivalent of) I took a coding class. We used Java (I think?) and I thought it was the most rewarding class I had ever taken. I had so much fun and actually finished the more advanced curriculum too in while taking the basic one (humble brag)

@sharon000 Round (x, digit=) is much simpeler indeed (more ways to Rome ğŸ‘). But it only does that trick. Substr() imo is much more diverse. It can extract certain numbers or letters and even replace them. Especially when your data contains all types of variables, it can be useful.

#TidyTuesday often contains numeric data with many decimals. Want to limit them? Gotta love substr(): it 
extracts or replaces a substring of a character string. 

Here, I deleted the last 4 decimals.

data4$grade <- substr(data4$grade, 1, nchar(data4$grade)-4)

mycols <- c("#04BEBF", "#006169", "#FFA28A","#9B0A12")
mycolors <- colorRampPalette(mycols)(41)

You don't necessarily need col_numb, however, I really like to write my code 'step-by-step'. Not only for me, but also for e.g. my students or colleagues when I share my codes.

So given a set of colors, this function will create a new color palette.

First, specify the number of colours you want. Then, take some colours you like (here I specify 4). By using colorRampPallette you take those 4 colours and 'multiply' them by the number of colours you need.

Colours!ğŸŒˆ

What if you need many colours? You can create your own palette! Especially, when you have a kid who picks your colours you need this one!

col_numb <- 41
mycols <- c("#04BEBF", "#006169", "#FFA28A","#9B0A12")
mycolors <- colorRampPalette(mycols)(col_numb)

Another common upsampling technique is Random Over Sampling ROSE. Check out R package 'ROSE' for implementation. Users can even combine over-sampling the minority class with under-sampling the majority class! https://t.co/BOwo4BtuRf 3/n

A commonly used resampling technique is SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique). 
There are different variations of this (e.g. Adaptive Neighbor SMOTE , Borderline-SMOTE, Density-based SMOTE). Check out R package 'smotefamily' https://t.co/kSD48BrGdT
ml 2/n

A common issue in #DataAnalytics is imbalanced data (rare-event prediction). Most classifiers do not perform very well and some resampling technique is required.
#Rstats #MachineLearning 1/n

I've been trying to think of a way to analyze phonotactic rules of R packages! My first step was pulling the names of packages from CRAN using rvest https://t.co/kuPXcpeF2g
How do you pronounce stringr?
How do you pronounce plyr?
Letâ€™s survey: How do you pronounce tidyr?

@kelkelphysics Iâ€™ve heard both a stressed and unstressed R for dplyr and stringr. For dplyr and plyr i think it might be natural for the R to be unstressed because â€œplierâ€ is already a word. â€œStringerâ€ is also a word but much less frequent?
If using R as its own syllable is pretty frequent for #rstats packages, is it a special phonotactic rule for R packages?

A really nice example of phonotactics at work with #rstats packages is pronouncing "rvest" as AR-vest and saying "roxygen2" where the R is not its own syllable. But recently, I heard someone say AR-oxygen! and I was like ğŸ˜®

I'd like to think there are phonotactic patterns for #rstats package names. Specifically, there are good amount of packages that end with an R (tidyr, plyr, dplyr, stringr). And I've heard these pronounced with the R stressed or unstressed: tidy-AR vs. tidier

An example of phonotactic knowledge in English: the "q" sound is usually followed by a vowel in word initial position (e.g., "queen"). q's aren't phonotactically plausible in consonant clusters (e.g., an English speaker can't imagine a pronunciation for qluick)
As part of my dissertation, I am looking at how phonotactic knowledge, or rules of the sound patterns in our language, influences word recognition.

With neuropsychological data from ADNI, I've done some Factor Analysis using R, there are a couple of useful packages for that.

Hi #RLadies! My time as curator has come to an end. Iâ€™ve enjoyed talking about my work and how I use #rstats this week. Follow me at @ade__lady for more discussion of genetics, stats, diversity & inclusion, etc. âœ¨âœ¨have a nice weekendâœ¨âœ¨

QTL mapping is a systematic way to test for association between each marker in the genome with variation in your phenotype of interest. In my lab, we use a linear regression modeling approach to identify QTL.

In addition to the transcriptional analyses that I've talked about earlier this week, the other reason I use #rstats is for quantitative trait locus mapping. A quantitative trait locus is a region of the genome that is associated with variation in a phenotype of interest.

What types of transcriptional pathways are affected by ozone? How does common genetic variation disrupt or alter the activity of those pathways? And most broadly, how does common genetic variation influence susceptibility to the toxic effects of ozone exposure?
My project focuses on the common air pollutant, ozone. I use genomic and genetic approaches to understand a few key themes.
As I mentioned previously, I'm pursuing a PhD in genetics & molecular biology. The lab I work in is interested in understanding/identifying genetic determinants of lung diseases and pathologies.
Happy Friday! Today, I'll talk through a potpourri of final topics, including further discussion of my PhD work.

I encourage my students to use Rmd/R notebooks for their work, and to comment for the sake of their future selves and those who might read the code that they write.
@fjtweedie Hi Fiona! I have one student talk through the problem and give the general structure/idea of what should be coded, and then the other student translates those ideas into the code.
For those of you who teach #rstats, what strategies do you like to employ? For students, what teaching methods have been most helpful for you in learning?

If I'm teaching more than one student, I utilize pair coding as well -- one student narrates while the other student writes the code and vice versa. This is a strategy that I've found especially helpful when I have students from varying skill levels!
We walk through homework problems together (after it's been graded), and compare my solutions to theirs. Coding is more creative than people realize, and many solutions exist for the same problem!

Many of my students come in with some programming experience, so we can jump right into higher level applications of R. For beginners, we walk through the syntax and basic functions in R. We use R early and often so that their familiarity grows and their apprehension shrinks ğŸ˜Š

Before I start working with any new students, I try to gauge their background and interests. For example, I'm currently working with a student who's interested in cancer biology & RNA-seq analysis, so I try to incorporate examples in my lessons that are relevant to those topics.
